 England":"Great Bromley, Essex, England"," Great Bromley, Essex, England":"Great Bromley, Essex, England"},"nl":{"1498–1580":"1498–1580","1498–1590":"1498–1590","1519–1574":"1519–1574","1569":"1569","1558":"1558","1498":"1498","1574":"1574","17 May 1519":"17 mei 1519","1571":"1571","24 December 1574":"24 december 1574","1580":"1580","1519":"1519","1590":"1590","1549":"1549","Guildford, Surrey, England":"Guildford, Surrey, England","Great Bromley, Essex, England":"Great Bromley, Essex, England"," Great Bromley, Essex, England":"Great Bromley, Essex, England"},"en":{"1498–1580":"1498–1580","1498–1590":"1498–1590","1519–1574":"1519–1574","1569":"1569","1558":"1558","1498":"1498","1574":"1574","17 May 1519":"17 May 1519","1571":"1571","24 December 1574":"24 December 1574","1580":"1580","1519":"1519","1590":"1590","1549":"1549","Guildford, Surrey, England":"Guildford, Surrey, England","Great Bromley, Essex, England":"Great Bromley, Essex, England"," Great Bromley, Essex, England":"Great Bromley, Essex, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Richard","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."],"variants":[{"name":"Rikert","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."]},{"name":"Rickert","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705201,"age":51,"year":"1549","julianDay":2286821,"title":"Book of Common Prayer","description":"Book of Common Prayer, a product of the English Reformation, was published in 1549 for assistance in the administration of the sacraments and other rites and ceremonies of the church according to the use of the Church of England. The book outlined morning, evening, and communion prayers and orders for baptism and marriage, thus making England a truly Protestant state.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Book_of_Common_Prayer","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Book of Common Prayer","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705202,"age":60,"year":"1558","julianDay":2290108,"title":"Act of Uniformity","description":"The Act of Uniformity was passed by the Parliament of England and required all people to go to church once a week. The consequence of not attending church was a fine of 12 pence, which was a considerable amount for a poor person.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705205,"age":71,"year":"1569","julianDay":2294126,"title":"State Lottery","description":"A State Lottery was recorded in 1569. The tickets were sold at St. Paul's Cathedral in London.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705206,"age":73,"year":"1571","julianDay":2294856,"title":"The Royal Exchange is Organized","description":"The Royal Exchange was organized in January 1571 by Sir Thomas Gresham. Gresham is known as the father of English banking.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"Richard William Morthdon was born in 1498, in Great Bromley, Essex, England. He had at least 1 daughter with Agnes Millington. He died in 1580, in his hometown, at the age of 82."},"et":{"1498–1580":"1498–1580","1498–1590":"1498–1590","1519–1574":"1519–1574","1569":"1569","1558":"1558","1498":"1498","1574":"1574","17 May 1519":"17. mai 1519","1571":"1571","24 December 1574":"24. detsember 1574","1580":"1580","1519":"1519","1590":"1590","1549":"1549","Guildford, Surrey, England":"Guildford, Surrey, England","Great Bromley, Essex, England":"Great Bromley, Essex, England"," Great Bromley, Essex, England":"Great Bromley, Essex, England"},"fi":{"1498–1580":"1498–1580","1498–1590":"1498–1590","1519–1574":"1519–1574","1569":"1569","1558":"1558","1498":"1498","1574":"1574","17 May 1519":"17. toukokuuta 1519","1571":"1571","24 December 1574":"24. joulukuuta 1574","1580":"1580","1519":"1519","1590":"1590","1549":"1549","Guildford, Surrey, England":"Guildford, Surrey, England","Great Bromley, Essex, England":"Great Bromley, Essex, England"," Great Bromley, Essex, England":"Great Bromley, Essex, England"},"fr":{"1498–1580":"1498–1580","1498–1590":"1498–1590","1519–1574":"